CryoToolBox.piping

Utilities for hydraulics calculations.

Contains functions for hydrodynamic calculations. The main source of the equations is Crane TP-410.

  43def _load_table(table_name):
  44    yaml_table = load((os.path.join(__location__, table_name)))
  45    result = {}
  46    for D, sub_table in yaml_table.items():
  47        result.update({D: {k: v*ureg.inch for k, v in sub_table.items()}})
  48    return result
  49
  50
  51NPS_table = _load_table('NPS_table.yaml')
  52COPPER_TABLE = _load_table('copper_table.yaml')

  57class PipingElement(ABC):
  58    """Generic piping element."""
  59
  60    @property
  61    @abstractmethod
  62    def area(self):
  63        pass
  64
  65    @abstractmethod
  66    def K(Re):
  67        pass
  68
  69    @abstractmethod
  70    def __str__(self):
  71        pass

  74class Tube(PipingElement):
  75    """
  76    Tube, requires OD and wall thickness specified
  77    """
  78    def __init__(self, OD, wall=0*ureg.m, L=0*ureg.m, c=0*ureg.m, wall_tol=None,
  79                 eps=0.0018*ureg.inch):
  80        """Generate tube object.
  81
  82        Parameters
  83        ----------
  84        OD : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
  85            Outer diameter of the tube.
  86        wall : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
  87            Wall thickness of the tube.
  88        T : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
  89            Minimum wall thickness considering manufacturer's minus tolerance.
  90        L : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
  91            Length of the tube.
  92        c : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
  93            Sum of the mechanical allowances plus corrosion and erosion
  94            allowances. Default is 0 m.
  95        eps : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
  96            Absolute roughness for the tube. Default value for smooth
  97            pipe.
  98        """
  99        self.OD = OD
 100        self.D = OD.to(ureg.inch).magnitude
 101        self.wall = wall
 102        self.L = L
 103        self.eps = eps
 104        # Wall thickness under tolerance is 12.5% as per ASTM A999
 105        self.wall_tol = wall_tol or (0.125*self.wall)
 106        self.T = wall - self.wall_tol
 107        self.c = c
 108        # c = Q_('0.5 mm') for unspecified machined surfaces
 109        # TODO add calculation for c based on thread depth c = h of B1.20.1
 110        self.type = 'Tube'
 111
 112    @property
 113    def ID(self):
 114        """ureg.Quantity {length: 1} : Wall thickness of Pipe based on NPS table.
 115        """
 116        return self.OD - 2*self.wall
 117
 118    @property
 119    def area(self):
 120        """ureg.Quantity {length: 2} : Cross sectional area of pipe.
 121        """
 122        return circle_area(self.ID)
 123
 124    @property
 125    def volume(self):
 126        """ureg.Quantity {length: 3} : Pipe inner volume.
 127        """
 128        return self.area * self.L
 129
 130    def K(self, Re_):
 131        """ureg.Quantity {length: 1}: Resistance coefficient.
 132        """
 133        eps_r = self.eps / self.ID
 134        K = f_Darcy(Re_, eps_r)*self.L/self.ID
 135        return float(K)
 136
 137    def f_T(self):
 138        """Calculate Darcy friction factor for complete turbulence for smooth
 139        pipe.
 140
 141        Returns
 142        -------
 143        ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}
 144            Fully turbulent Darcy friction factor.
 145        """
 146        return 1 / (4*log10(self.eps/(3.7*self.ID))**2)
 147
 148    def pressure_design_thick(self, P_int, P_ext=P_NTP, *, S, E, W, Y):
 149        """Calculate pressure design thickness for given pressure and pipe
 150        material based on B31.3 304.1.
 151
 152        Parameters
 153        ----------
 154        P_int : ureg.Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -2}
 155            Internal pressure, absolute
 156        P_ext : ureg.Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -2}
 157            External pressure, absolute
 158
 159        Returns
 160        -------
 161        ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 162            Minimum required wall thickness.
 163        """
 164        logger.warning('Deprecated, use standalone function instead.')
 165        P_diff = P_int - P_ext
 166        return pressure_design_thick(self, P_diff, I=1, S=S, E=E, W=W, Y=Y)
 167
 168    def pressure_rating(self, *, S, E, W, Y):
 169        """Calculate internal pressure rating.
 170
 171        Based on B31.3 304.1.
 172
 173        Returns
 174        -------
 175        ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 176            Minimum required wall thickness.
 177        """
 178        logger.warning('Deprecated, use standalone function instead.')
 179        return pressure_rating(self, S, E, W, Y)
 180
 181
 182    def __str__(self):
 183        return f'{self.type}, {self.OD:.3g~}x{self.wall:.3g~}, ' + \
 184            f'L={self.L:.3g~}'
 185
 186    # def __str__(self):
 187    #     return f'{self.D:.3g}" {self.type}'

 190class Pipe(Tube):
 191    """NPS pipe class.
 192
 193    Pipe objects represent actual parts of the pipeline. The Pipe object
 194    will contain information such as OD, ID, wall thickness, and can be
 195    used to calculate flow coefficient K that is used for flow calculations.
 196    """
 197    def __init__(self, D_nom, SCH=40, L=0*ureg.m, c=Q_('0 mm'),
 198                 eps=0.0018*ureg.inch):
 199        """Generate `Pipe` object.
 200
 201        Parameters
 202        ----------
 203        D_nom : float or ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 204            Nominal diameter of piping; can be dimensionless or having a unit
 205            of length.
 206        SCH : int
 207            Pipe schedule. Default value is SCH 40 (STD).
 208        L : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 209            Pipe length
 210        c : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 211            Sum of the mechanical allowances plus corrosion and erosion
 212            allowances.
 213        eps : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 214            Absolute roughness for the tube. Default value for smooth
 215            pipe.
 216        """
 217        if isinstance(D_nom, ureg.Quantity):
 218            D = D_nom.magnitude
 219        else:
 220            D = D_nom
 221        OD = NPS_table[D]['OD']
 222        self.SCH = SCH
 223        # TODO Should I be using get here?
 224        wall = NPS_table[D].get(SCH)
 225        if wall is None:
 226            raise PipingError(f'SCH {SCH} not available for pipe size {D}.')
 227        super().__init__(OD, wall, L=L, c=c, eps=eps)
 228        self.D = D
 229        self.type = 'NPS pipe'
 230
 231    def __str__(self):
 232        return f'{self.type} {self.D}" SCH {self.SCH}, L={self.L:.3~g}'
 233

 235class CopperTube(Tube):
 236    """Copper tube.
 237
 238    Parameters
 239    ----------
 240    OD : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 241        Outer diameter of the tube.
 242    wall : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 243        Wall thickness of the tube.
 244    L : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 245        Length of the tube.
 246    eps : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 247        Absolute roughness for the tube. Default value for smooth
 248        pipe.
 249    """
 250    def __init__(self, D_nom, type_='K', L=0*ureg.m,
 251                 eps=0.0018*ureg.inch):
 252        if isinstance(D_nom, ureg.Quantity):
 253            D = D_nom.magnitude
 254        else:
 255            D = D_nom
 256        OD = COPPER_TABLE[D]['OD']
 257        wall = COPPER_TABLE[D][type_]
 258        c = 0 * ureg.inch  # Not affected by corrosion
 259        super().__init__(OD, wall, L=L, c=c, eps=eps)
 260        self.D = D
 261        self.type = 'Copper tube Type ' + type_
 262

 264class VJPipe(Pipe):
 265    """Vacuum jacketed pipe.
 266    """
 267    def __init__(self, D_nom, *, SCH=5, L=0*ureg.m,
 268                 VJ_D, VJ_SCH=5, c=0*ureg.inch):
 269        """Generate Vacuum jacketed pipe object.
 270
 271        Parameters
 272        ----------
 273        D_nom : float or ureg.Quantity {length: 1}

 277        L : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}

 296class CorrugatedPipe(Tube):
 297    """Corrugated pipe class.
 298    """
 299    def __init__(self, D_nom, L=0*ureg.m):
 300        """Generate corrugated pipe object.
 301
 302        Parameters
 303        ----------
 304        D_nom : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 305            Nominal diameter of the inner pipe.
 306        L : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 307            Length of the pipe.
 308        """
 309        # TODO DRY
 310        OD = D_nom
 311        logger.debug('For corrugated piping assumed OD = D')
 312        wall = 0 * ureg.m
 313        c = 0 * ureg.inch
 314        # Friction factor multiplicator usually in 2.2..2.6 range
 315        self.f_mult = 2.6
 316        super().__init__(OD, wall, L, c)
 317        self.type = 'Corrugated pipe'
 318        logger.debug('For corrugated piping assumed wall = 0')
 319
 320    def K(self, Re_):
 321        return self.f_mult * super().K(Re_)  # Multiplier 4 is used for corrugated pipe
 322
 323    def branch_reinforcement(self):
 324        raise NotImplementedError('Branch reinforcement not implemented for'
 325                                  ' corrugated pipe')
 326
 327    def pressure_design_thick(self):
 328        raise NotImplementedError('Pressure design thickness not implemented'
 329                                  ' for corrugated pipe')
 330
 331    def __str__(self):
 332        return f'Corrugated pipe D={self.OD:.3g~}, L={self.L:.3g~}'

 423class ConicOrifice(Orifice):

 429        Parameters

 432        ID : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}

 450class Annulus(PipingElement):
 451    """"Annulus or tube in tube.
 452
 453    Parameters
 454    ----------
 455    D1 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 456        ID of the outer tube.
 457    D2 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 458        OD of the inner tube.
 459    L : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 460        Length of the annulus tube.
 461    """
 462    def __init__(self, D1, D2, L=Q_('0m'), eps=0.0018*ureg.inch):
 463        self.D1 = D1
 464        self.D2 = D2
 465        assert D1 > D2, 'D1 should be larger than D2'
 466        self.L = L
 467        assert D1 > D2
 468        self._area = pi / 4 * (D1**2 - D2**2)
 469        self.volume = self.area * L
 470        self.ID = D1 - D2  # Hydraulic diameter
 471        self.eps = eps
 472
 473    @property
 474    def area(self):
 475        return self._area
 476
 477    def K(self, Re_):
 478        return Tube.K(self, Re_)
 479
 480    def __str__(self):
 481        return f'Annulus D1={self.D1:.3g~}, D2={self.D2:.3g~}, L={self.L:.3g~}'
 482
 483    # def __str__(self):
 484    #     return f'{self.D1:.3g~} x {self.D2:.3g~} annulus'

 487class Elbow(Tube):
 488    """
 489    NPS elbow fitting.
 490    MRO makes method K from PipeElbow class to override method from Pipe class.
 491    """
 492    def __init__(self, OD, wall=0*ureg.inch, c=0*ureg.inch, R_D=1.5, N=1,
 493                 angle=90*ureg.deg):
 494        """Generate a tube elbow object.
 495
 496        Parameters
 497        ----------
 498        OD : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 499            Outer diameter of the tube.
 500        wall : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 501            Wall thickness of the tube.
 502        R_D : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 503            Elbow radius/diameter ratio
 504        N : int
 505            Number of elbows in the pipeline
 506        angle : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}
 507            Number of elbows in the pipeline
 508        """
 509        self.R_D = R_D
 510        self.N = N
 511        self.angle = angle
 512        super().__init__(OD, wall, L=0*ureg.m, c=c)
 513        self.L = R_D*self.ID*angle
 514        self.type = 'Tube elbow'
 515
 516    def K(self, Re_):
 517        """
 518        Pressure drop in an elbow fitting.
 519        Based on Handbook of Hydraulic Resistance by I.E. Idelchik.
 520        """
 521        if self.angle <= 70*ureg.deg:
 522            A1 = 0.9*sin(self.angle)
 523        elif self.angle == 90*ureg.deg:
 524            A1 = 1
 525        elif self.angle >= 100*ureg.deg:
 526            A1 = 0.7+0.35*self.angle/(90*ureg.deg)
 527        else:
 528            logger.error('''Improper bend angle for elbow.
 529            90 degrees used instead: {}'''.format(self.angle))
 530            A1 = 1
 531
 532        if self.R_D < 1:
 533            B1 = 0.21*(self.R_D)**(-0.25)
 534        else:
 535            B1 = 0.21*(self.R_D)**(-0.5)
 536
 537        C1 = 1  # use different value for non-axis symmetric
 538        # Friction losses in the elbow
 539        K_frict = super().K(Re_)
 540        return (A1*B1*C1+K_frict)*self.N
 541
 542    def __str__(self):
 543        return f'{self.N}x {self.type}, {self.OD}"x{self.wall}", ' + \
 544            f'{self.angle.to(ureg.deg)}, R_D = {self.R_D}'
 545

 547class PipeElbow(Elbow, Pipe):
 548    """
 549    NPS Elbow fitting.
 550    MRO makes method K from Elbow class to override method from Pipe class.
 551    """
 552    def __init__(self, D_nom, SCH=40, c=0*ureg.inch, R_D=1.5, N=1,
 553                 angle=90*ureg.deg):
 554        """Generate a pipe elbow object.
 555
 556        Parameters
 557        ----------
 558        D_nom : float or ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 559            Nominal diameter of piping; can be dimensionless or having a unit
 560            of length.
 561        SCH : int
 562            Pipe schedule. Default value is SCH 40 (STD).
 563        R_D : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 564            Elbow radius/diameter ratio
 565        N : int
 566            Number of elbows in the pipeline
 567        angle : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}
 568            Number of elbows in the pipeline
 569        """
 570        # D_nom and SCH go as positional arguments to Pipe __init__
 571        super().__init__(D_nom, SCH, c=c, R_D=R_D, N=N, angle=angle)
 572        self.type = 'NPS elbow'
 573
 574    def __str__(self):
 575        return f'{self.N}x {self.type}, {self.D}" SCH {self.SCH}, ' + \
 576            f'{self.angle.to(ureg.deg)}, R_D = {self.R_D}'

 579class Tee(Tube):
 580    """
 581    Tee fitting.
 582    """
 583    def __init__(self, OD, wall=0*ureg.inch, c=0*ureg.inch, direction='thru',
 584                 N=1):
 585        """Generate a tee.
 586
 587        Parameters
 588        ----------
 589        OD : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 590            Outer diameter of the tube.
 591        wall : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 592            Wall thickness of the tube.
 593        c : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 594            Sum of the mechanical allowances plus corrosion and erosion
 595            allowances of the inner pipe.
 596        N : int
 597            Number of tees in the pipeline
 598        """
 599        if direction in ['thru', 'through', 'run']:
 600            self.direction = 'run'
 601        elif direction in ['branch', 'side']:
 602            self.direction = 'branch'
 603        else:
 604            logger.error('''Tee direction is not recognized,
 605                         try "thru" or "branch": {}'''.format(direction))
 606        L = 0*ureg.m
 607        super().__init__(OD, wall, L, c)
 608        self.N = N
 609        self.type = 'Tube tee'
 610
 611    def K(self, Re=None):
 612        # TODO Add Re handling
 613        if self.direction == 'run':
 614            K_ = 20*self.f_T()  # Crane TP-410 p. A-29
 615        elif self.direction == 'branch':
 616            K_ = 60*self.f_T()  # Crane TP-410 p. A-29
 617        return self.N * K_
 618
 619    def __str__(self):
 620        return f'{self.type}, {self.OD}x{self.wall}, {self.direction}'

 696
 697class PipingTransition(PipingElement):
 698    """
 699    Base class for pipe diameter transitions (contractions and enlargements).
 700    """
 701
 702    def _init_transition(self, ID1, ID2, theta, transition_type):
 703        """
 704        Common initialization for diameter transitions.
 705
 706        Parameters
 707        ----------
 708        ID1 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 709            Upstream pipe inside diameter.
 710        ID2 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 711            Downstream pipe inside diameter.
 712        theta : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}
 713            Transition angle.
 714        transition_type : str
 715            Type of transition ('Contraction' or 'Enlargement').
 716        """
 717        # Validate angle (common to both)
 718        if theta <= 0*ureg.deg or theta > 180*ureg.deg:
 719            raise ValueError(f"Transition angle must be in range (0°, 180°], "
 720                           f"got {theta}")
 721
 722        self.ID1 = ID1
 723        self.ID2 = ID2
 724        self.theta = theta
 725        self.beta = beta(ID1, ID2)
 726        self.type = transition_type
 727        self.OD = None
 728
 729        # Use smaller diameter for area reference
 730        self.ID = min(ID1, ID2)
 731        self._area = circle_area(self.ID)
 732
 733        # Calculate axial length
 734        self.L = abs(ID1 - ID2) / (2 * tan(theta/2))
 735
 736        # Calculate internal volume (truncated cone)
 737        r1 = ID1 / 2
 738        r2 = ID2 / 2
 739        self.volume = pi * self.L / 3 * (r1**2 + r1*r2 + r2**2)
 740
 741    def __str__(self):
 742        """
 743        String representation of the piping transition.
 744
 745        Returns
 746        -------
 747        str
 748            Human-readable description of the contraction.
 749        """
 750        return (f'{self.type}, {self.theta.to(ureg.deg)} from '
 751                f'{self.ID1.to(ureg.inch):.3f} to {self.ID2.to(ureg.inch):.3f}')
 752
 753    def __repr__(self):
 754        """
 755        Detailed string representation for debugging.
 756
 757        Returns
 758        -------
 759        str
 760            Detailed representation showing all key parameters.
 761        """
 762        return (f"Contraction(ID1={self.ID1}, ID2={self.ID2}, "
 763                f"theta={self.theta})")

 766class Contraction(PipingTransition):
 767    """
 768    Sudden and gradual pipe contraction fitting based on Crane TP-410.
 769
 770    This class represents pipe contractions that reduce flow area from a larger
 771    upstream pipe to a smaller downstream pipe. The pressure loss coefficient
 772    is calculated based on the contraction angle and diameter ratio according
 773    to Crane TP-410 standards.
 774
 775    Parameters
 776    ----------
 777    ID1 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 778        Inside diameter of upstream (larger) pipe.
 779    ID2 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 780        Inside diameter of downstream (smaller) pipe.
 781    theta : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}, optional
 782        Total contraction angle (included angle), by default 180°.
 783        Valid range is 0° < theta ≤ 180°.
 784
 785    Attributes
 786    ----------
 787    beta : float
 788        Diameter ratio (ID2/ID1), dimensionless.
 789    theta : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}
 790        Contraction angle.
 791    type : str
 792        Element type identifier.
 793    ID1 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 794        Upstream pipe inside diameter.
 795    ID2 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 796        Downstream pipe inside diameter.
 797    ID : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 798        Minimum (downstream) inside diameter.
 799    L : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 800        Axial length of contraction.
 801    volume : ureg.Quantity {length: 3}
 802        Internal volume of the contraction.
 803
 804    Notes
 805    -----
 806    The pressure loss coefficient K is calculated using different formulas
 807    depending on the contraction angle:
 808
 809    For θ ≤ 45°:
 810    .. math:: K = 0.8 \\sin(\\theta/2) (1 - \\beta^2)
 811
 812    For 45° < θ ≤ 180°:
 813    .. math:: K = 0.5 (1 - \\beta^2) \\sqrt{\\sin(\\theta/2)}
 814
 815    Where β = ID2/ID1 is the diameter ratio.
 816
 817    The axial length is calculated as:
 818    .. math:: L = \\frac{|ID_1 - ID_2|}{2 \\tan(\\theta/2)}
 819
 820    References
 821    ----------
 822    Crane Technical Paper No. 410 (TP-410), Flow of Fluids Through Valves,
 823    Fittings, and Pipe, Section A-26.
 824
 825    Examples
 826    --------
 827    >>> import CryoToolBox as ctb
 828    >>> u = ctb.ureg
 829    >>> # Sudden contraction from 4" to 2" pipe
 830    >>> contraction = ctb.piping.Contraction(4*u.inch, 2*u.inch)
 831    >>> contraction.beta
 832    0.5
 833    >>> contraction.K()
 834    0.375
 835
 836    >>> # Gradual 30° contraction
 837    >>> gradual = ctb.piping.Contraction(4*u.inch, 2*u.inch, 30*u.deg)
 838    >>> gradual.K()
 839    0.1552...
 840    """
 841
 842    def __init__(self, ID1, ID2, theta=ureg('180 deg')):
 843        """
 844        Initialize contraction fitting.
 845
 846        Parameters
 847        ----------
 848        ID1 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 849            Inside diameter of upstream pipe.
 850        ID2 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 851            Inside diameter of downstream pipe.
 852        theta : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}, optional
 853            Contraction angle, by default 180°.
 854
 855        Raises
 856        ------
 857        ValueError
 858            If ID1 <= ID2 (not a contraction).
 859            If theta is outside valid range (0°, 180°].
 860        """
 861        # Input validation
 862        if ID1 <= ID2:
 863            raise ValueError(f"ID1 ({ID1}) must be greater than ID2 ({ID2}) "
 864                           "for a contraction")
 865
 866        if theta <= 0*ureg.deg or theta > 180*ureg.deg:
 867            raise ValueError(f"Contraction angle must be in range (0°, 180°], "
 868                           f"got {theta}")
 869
 870        self._init_transition(ID1, ID2, theta, 'Contraction')
 871
 872    @property
 873    def area(self):
 874        """
 875        Cross-sectional area of the downstream (smaller) pipe.
 876
 877        Returns
 878        -------
 879        ureg.Quantity {length: 2}
 880            Flow area based on downstream diameter.
 881        """
 882        return self._area
 883
 884    def K(self, Re=None):
 885        """
 886        Calculate pressure loss coefficient for the contraction.
 887
 888        Parameters
 889        ----------
 890        Re : float, optional
 891            Reynolds number. Currently not implemented but reserved
 892            for future Reynolds number corrections.
 893
 894        Returns
 895        -------
 896        float
 897            Dimensionless pressure loss coefficient based on downstream
 898            velocity head.
 899
 900        Notes
 901        -----
 902        The loss coefficient is calculated using Crane TP-410 formulas:
 903
 904        - For θ ≤ 45°: K = 0.8 sin(θ/2) (1 - β²)
 905        - For θ > 45°: K = 0.5 (1 - β²) √sin(θ/2)
 906
 907        Where β = ID2/ID1 is the diameter ratio.
 908
 909        Raises
 910        ------
 911        ValueError
 912            If theta > 180° (invalid contraction angle).
 913
 914        Examples
 915        --------
 916        >>> import CryoToolBox as ctb
 917        >>> u = ctb.ureg
 918        >>> contraction = Contraction(4*u.inch, 2*u.inch, 90*u.deg)
 919        >>> contraction.K()
 920        0.3153...
 921        """
 922        # TODO: Add Re handling for Reynolds number corrections
 923        if Re is not None:
 924            logger.warning("Reynolds number correction not yet implemented")
 925
 926        if self.theta <= 45*ureg.deg:
 927            # Crane TP-410 A-26, Formula 1 for gradual contractions
 928            K_ = 0.8 * sin(self.theta/2) * (1 - self.beta**2)
 929        elif self.theta <= 180*ureg.deg:
 930            # Crane TP-410 A-26, Formula 2 for sudden contractions
 931            K_ = 0.5 * (1 - self.beta**2) * sqrt(sin(self.theta/2))
 932        else:
 933            raise ValueError(f'Contraction angle cannot exceed 180°, '
 934                           f'got {self.theta.to(ureg.deg)}')
 935
 936        return float(K_)
 937

 939class Enlargement(PipingTransition):
 940    """
 941    Sudden and gradual pipe enlargement fitting based on Crane TP-410.
 942
 943    This class represents pipe enlargements that increase flow area from a smaller
 944    upstream pipe to a larger downstream pipe. The pressure loss coefficient
 945    is calculated based on the enlargement angle and diameter ratio.
 946
 947    Parameters
 948    ----------
 949    ID1 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 950        Inside diameter of upstream (smaller) pipe.
 951    ID2 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 952        Inside diameter of downstream (larger) pipe.
 953    theta : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}, optional
 954        Total enlargement angle (included angle), by default 180°.
 955
 956    Notes
 957    -----
 958    For enlargements, the pressure loss coefficient is based on upstream
 959    velocity head and uses different formulas than contractions.
 960    """
 961
 962    def __init__(self, ID1, ID2, theta=ureg('180 deg')):
 963        """
 964        Initialize enlargement fitting.
 965
 966        Parameters
 967        ----------
 968        ID1 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 969            Inside diameter of upstream (smaller) pipe.
 970        ID2 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
 971            Inside diameter of downstream (larger) pipe.
 972        theta : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}, optional
 973            Enlargement angle, by default 180°.
 974
 975        Raises
 976        ------
 977        ValueError
 978            If ID1 >= ID2 (not an enlargement).
 979            If theta is outside valid range (0°, 180°].
 980        """
 981        # Enlargement-specific validation
 982        if ID1 >= ID2:
 983            raise ValueError(f"ID2 ({ID2}) must be greater than ID1 ({ID1}) "
 984                           "for an enlargement")
 985
 986        # Use shared initialization
 987        self._init_transition(ID1, ID2, theta, 'Enlargement')
 988
 989    @property
 990    def area(self):
 991        """
 992        Cross-sectional area of the upstream (smaller) pipe.
 993
 994        Returns
 995        -------
 996        ureg.Quantity {length: 2}
 997            Flow area based on upstream diameter for enlargements.
 998        """
 999        return circle_area(self.ID1)  # Use upstream area for enlargements
1000
1001    def K(self, Re=None):
1002        """
1003        Calculate pressure loss coefficient for the enlargement.
1004
1005        Parameters
1006        ----------
1007        Re : float, optional
1008            Reynolds number. Currently not implemented.
1009
1010        Returns
1011        -------
1012        float
1013            Dimensionless pressure loss coefficient based on upstream
1014            velocity head.
1015
1016        Notes
1017        -----
1018        Enlargement formulas differ from contractions and are based on
1019        upstream velocity head.
1020        """
1021        # Enlargement-specific K calculation
1022        # (Implementation depends on your specific enlargement formulas)
1023        if self.theta <= 45*ureg.deg:
1024            # Gradual enlargement formula
1025            K_ = 2.6 * sin(self.theta/2) * (1 - self.beta**2)**2
1026        else:
1027            # Sudden enlargement formula: K = (1 - β²)²
1028            K_ = (1 - self.beta**2)**2
1029
1030        return float(K_)

1033class PackedBed(PipingElement):
1034    """Packed bed piping element.
1035
1036    Attributes
1037    ----------
1038    ID : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
1039        Inner diameter of the shell of the packed bed.
1040    L : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
1041        Height of the packed bed.
1042    D_part : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
1043        Spherical equivalent particle diameter.
1044    eps : float
1045        Void fraction (porosity) of the bed.
1046    """
1047    def __init__(self, ID, height, D_part, eps):
1048        self.ID = ID
1049        self.OD = self.ID
1050        self.L = height
1051        self.D_part = D_part
1052        self.eps = eps
1053        self.type = 'Packed bed'
1054
1055    @property
1056    def area(self):
1057        return pi * self.ID**2 / 4
1058
1059    def f(self, Re_s):
1060        """Calculate packed bed friction factor."""
1061        return 150/self.Re_mod(Re_s) + 1.75
1062
1063    def Re_mod(self, Re_s):
1064        """Calculate modified Reynolds number for the packed bed.
1065
1066        Parameters
1067        ----------
1068        Re_s : Quantity {dimensionless} or float
1069            Superficial Re number; Re_s = U_s*ID*rho/mu,
1070            where U_s - superficial velocity and ID - shell ID.
1071        """
1072        Re_ = Re_s * self.D_part/(self.ID*(1-self.eps))
1073        return Re_.to_base_units()
1074
1075    def K(self, Re_s):
1076        """Calculate resistance coefficient for the packed bed."""
1077        K_ = 2*self.f(Re_s)*self.L*(1-self.eps) / \
1078            (self.D_part*self.eps**3)
1079        return K_.to_base_units()
1080
1081    def __str__(self):
1082        return (f'{self.type} ID={self.ID:.3g~}, L={self.L:.3g~}, '
1083                f'eps={self.eps:.3g}, D={self.D_part:.3g~}')

1088class ParallelPlateRelief:
1089    def __init__(self, Springs, Plate, Supply_pipe):
1090        """
1091        Initiate Parallel Plate instance.
1092        Parallel Plate relief valve designed by Fermilab
1093
1094        Springs: dictionary containing 'N' - number of springs, 'k' - spring rate, and 'dx_precomp' - pre-compression length
1095        Plate: dictionary containing 'OD_plate' - OD of the plate, 'OD_O_ring' - OD of the O-Ring installed, and 'W_plate' - plate weight
1096        Supply_pipe: Pipe/Tube object of upstream pipe
1097        """
1098        self.Springs = Springs
1099        self.Plate = Plate
1100        self.Supply_pipe = Supply_pipe
1101
1102    def P_set(self):
1103        """"
1104        Calculate set (lift) pressure of the Parallel Plate relief
1105        """
1106        # Before lifting pressure affects area within O-Ring OD
1107        A_lift = pi * self.Plate['OD_O_ring']**2 / 4
1108        F_precomp = self.Springs['N'] * self.Springs['k'] *\
1109            self.Springs['dx_precomp']
1110        # Force required to lift the plate
1111        F_lift = F_precomp + self.Plate['W_plate']
1112        self.F_lift = F_lift
1113        P_set = F_lift / A_lift
1114        return P_set.to(ureg.psi)
1115
1116    def P_open(self):
1117        """
1118        Calculate pressure required to fully open Parallel Plate relief
1119        """
1120        # compression required to provide vent area equal to supply pipe area
1121        dx_open = self.Supply_pipe.area / (pi*self.Plate['OD_plate'])
1122        # Force at fully open
1123        F_open = self.F_lift = self.Springs['N'] * self.Springs['k'] * dx_open
1124        # At fully open pressure is distributed as:
1125        # Full pressure for up to supply pipe diameter
1126        # Linear fall off up to plate OD
1127        A_open = self.Supply_pipe.area + pi/8*(self.Plate['OD_plate']**2 -
1128                                               self.Supply_pipe.ID**2)
1129        P_open = F_open / A_open
1130        return P_open.to(ureg.psi)
1131

1133# Supporting functions used for flow rate and pressure drop calculations.
1134def f_Darcy(Re_, eps_r, method='churchill'):
1135    """Calculate Darcy friction factor using Serghide solution to
1136    Colebrook equation.
1137
1138    See Crane TP-410 2013, equation 6-6.
1139
1140    Parameters
1141    ----------
1142    Re_ : float or Quantity {dimensionless}
1143        Reynolds number
1144    eps_r : float or Quantity {dimensionless}
1145        Absolute roughness of the pipe
1146    method : str
1147        Friction factor formula name
1148
1149    Returns
1150    -------
1151    float
1152        Darcy friction coefficient
1153    """
1154    if Re_ <= 2100:
1155        return 64 / Re_
1156    if method == 'churchill':
1157        return churchill(Re_, eps_r)
1158    elif method == 'serghide':
1159        return serghide(Re_, eps_r)
1160
1161
1162def churchill(Re_, eps_r):
1163    """Calculate Darcy friction factor using modified Churchill formula.
1164    See 8.5.2 of "Pipe flow, A Practical and Comprehensive Guide", Rennels,
1165    Hobart, Hudson, 2012.
1166
1167    Parameters
1168    ----------
1169    Re_ : float or Quantity {dimensionless}
1170        Reynolds number
1171    eps_r : float or Quantity {dimensionless}
1172        Relative roughness of the pipe
1173
1174    Returns
1175    -------
1176    float
1177        Darcy friction coefficient
1178    """
1179    A1 = 0.883 * log(Re_)**1.282 / Re_**1.007
1180    A2 = 0.27 * eps_r
1181    A3 = - 110 * eps_r / Re_
1182    A = (0.8687 * log(A1+A2+A3))**16
1183    B = (13269 / Re_)**16
1184    f = ((64/Re_)**12 + 1/(A+B)**(3/2))**(1/12)
1185    return f
1186
1187
1188def serghide(Re_, eps_r):
1189    """Calculate Darcy friction factor using Serghide solution to
1190    Colebrook equation.
1191
1192    See Crane TP-410 2013, equation 6-6.
1193
1194    Parameters
1195    ----------
1196    Re_ : float or Quantity {dimensionless}
1197        Reynolds number
1198    eps_r : float or Quantity {dimensionless}
1199        Relative roughness of the pipe
1200
1201    Returns
1202    -------
1203    float
1204        Darcy friction coefficient
1205    """
1206    A = -2 * log10(eps_r/3.7+12/Re_)
1207    B = -2 * log10(eps_r/3.7+2.51*A/Re_)
1208    C = -2 * log10(eps_r/3.7+2.51*B/Re_)
1209    f = (A - (B-A)**2/(C-2*B+A))**(-2)
1210    return f
1211
1212
1213def K_piping(m_dot, fluid, piping):
1214    """Calculate resistance coefficient converted to the area of the first element.
1215
1216    Parameters
1217    ----------
1218    piping : List[PipingElement]
1219    Returns
1220    -------
1221    tuple
1222        K0 : converted resistance coefficient of the piping
1223        A0 : area of the first element, basis for conversion
1224    """
1225    K0 = 0*ureg.dimensionless
1226    try:
1227        A0 = piping[0].area  # using area of the first element as base
1228    except IndexError:
1229        raise IndexError('Piping has no elements! '
1230                            'Use Piping.add to add sections to piping.')
1231    for element in piping:
1232        Re_ = Re(fluid, m_dot, element.ID, element.area)
1233        K_el = element.K(Re_) * (A0/element.area)**2
1234        K0 += K_el
1235    return (K0.to_base_units(), A0)
1236

1238def rc(fluid):
1239    """Calculate critical pressure drop for the given fluid."""
1240    k = fluid.gamma
1241    rc = (2/(k+1))**(k/(k-1))
1242    return rc
1243
1244
1245def dP_Darcy(K, rho, w):
1246    '''
1247    Darcy equation for pressure drop.
1248    K - resistance coefficient
1249    rho - density of flow at entrance
1250    w - flow speed
1251    '''
1252    d_P = K*rho*w**2/2
1253    return d_P.to(ureg.psi)
1254
1255
1256def dP_incomp(m_dot, fluid, piping):
1257    """Calculate pressure drop of incompressible flow through piping.
1258    Lumped method using Darcy equation is used.
1259    """
1260    P_0 = fluid.P
1261    T_0 = fluid.T
1262    rho_0 = fluid.Dmass
1263    K, area = K_piping(m_dot, fluid, piping)
1264    w = m_dot / (rho_0*area)
1265    return dP_Darcy(K, rho_0, w)
1266def dP_Darcy(K, rho, w):
1267    """
1268    Calculate pressure drop using the Darcy-Weisbach equation.
1269
1270    This function calculates the pressure drop across a pipe fitting or
1271    section using the standard form of the Darcy-Weisbach equation with
1272    a resistance coefficient K.
1273
1274    Parameters
1275    ----------
1276    K : float
1277        Dimensionless resistance coefficient (loss coefficient).
1278        Typical values:
1279        - Sharp-edged entrance: K ≈ 0.5
1280        - Well-rounded entrance: K ≈ 0.04
1281        - 90° elbow: K ≈ 0.9
1282        - Gate valve (fully open): K ≈ 0.15
1283    rho : ureg.Quantity {length: -3, mass: 1}
1284        Fluid density at flow conditions.
1285    w : ureg.Quantity {length: 1, time: -1}
1286        Flow velocity (speed) at the reference location.
1287
1288    Returns
1289    -------
1290    ureg.Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -2}
1291        Pressure drop in psi. Positive value indicates pressure loss
1292        in the direction of flow.
1293
1294    Notes
1295    -----
1296    The Darcy-Weisbach equation for pressure drop is:
1297
1298    .. math:: \\Delta P = K \\frac{\\rho w^2}{2}
1299
1300    where:
1301    - K is the dimensionless loss coefficient
1302    - ρ is the fluid density
1303    - w is the flow velocity
1304
1305    This equation assumes:
1306    - Incompressible flow
1307    - Steady-state conditions
1308    - K value appropriate for the flow conditions (Reynolds number)
1309
1310    The pressure drop represents the mechanical energy loss due to
1311    friction, turbulence, and flow separation.
1312
1313    References
1314    ----------
1315    - Crane Technical Paper No. 410 (TP-410)
1316
1317    Examples
1318    --------
1319    >>> import CryoToolBox as ctb
1320    >>> u = ctb.ureg
1321    >>> # Pressure drop across a 90° elbow
1322    >>> K_elbow = 0.2
1323    >>> rho_water = 1000 * u.kg / u.m**3
1324    >>> velocity = 2.5 * u.m / u.s
1325    >>> dP_Darcy(K_elbow, rho_water, velocity)
1326    <Quantity(6.25, 'millibar')>
1327    """
1328    # Input validation
1329    if K < 0:
1330        raise ValueError(f"Resistance coefficient K must be non-negative, got {K}")
1331    if rho.magnitude <= 0:
1332        raise ValueError(f"Density must be positive, got {rho}")
1333    if w.magnitude < 0:
1334        raise ValueError(f"Velocity magnitude must be non-negative, got {w}")
1335
1336    dP = K * rho * w**2 / 2
1337    return dP.to(ureg.mbar)
1338
1339def m_dot_incomp(fluid, piping, P_out=P_NTP, guess=1*ureg.g/ureg.s):
1340    '''Calculate mass flow through the piping using initial conditions
1341    at the beginning of piping.
1342
1343    Calculation is based on Crane TP-410, p. 1.9.
1344    Net expansion factor Y is conservatively assumed as 1.
1345    Mass flow is calculated using Darcy equation.
1346
1347    Parameters
1348    ----------
1349    P_out : ureg.Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -1}
1350        Exit pressure of the piping.
1351    guess : ureg.Quantity {mass: 1, time: -1}
1352        guess value for the mass flow rate
1353
1354    Returns
1355    -------
1356    ureg.Quantity : {mass: 1, time: -1}
1357    '''
1358    P_0 = fluid.P
1359    if P_0 <= P_out:
1360        raise HydraulicError(f'Input pressure less or equal to output: \
1361        {P_0.to(ureg.Pa):.3g}, {P_out.to(ureg.Pa):.3g}')
1362    def to_solve(m_dot_gs, P_in_Pa, P_out_Pa):
1363        dP_calc = dP_incomp(m_dot_gs*ureg.g/ureg.s, fluid, piping)
1364        dP_given = P_in_Pa - P_out_Pa
1365        return dP_given - dP_calc.m_as(ureg.Pa)
1366    P_in_Pa = P_0.m_as(ureg.Pa)
1367    P_out_Pa = P_out.m_as(ureg.Pa)
1368    args = (P_in_Pa, P_out_Pa)  # arguments passed to to_solve
1369    x0 = guess.m_as(ureg.g/ureg.s)
1370    x1 = x0 * 2  # Usually doubling the flow is OK estimate
1371    solution = root_scalar(to_solve, args, x0=x0, x1=x1)
1372    m_dot_ = solution.root * ureg.g/ureg.s
1373    return m_dot_
1374
1375
1376def m_dot_isot(fluid, pipe, P_out=P_NTP, m_dot_g=1*ureg.g/ureg.s, tol=1e-6):
1377    """Calculate mass flow rate through piping for isothermal compressible
1378    flow.
1379
1380    See 4.4 of "Pipe flow, A Practical and Comprehensive Guide", Rennels,
1381    Hobart, Hudson, 2012.
1382
1383    Parameters
1384    ----------
1385    fluid : ThermState
1386        Inlet fluid conditions
1387    pipe : Pipe
1388    P_out : ureg.Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -1}
1389        Exit pressure of the piping.
1390
1391    Returns
1392    -------
1393    Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -2}
1394        Pressure drop
1395    """
1396    P1 = fluid.P
1397    P2 = P_out
1398    T = fluid.T
1399    R = fluid.specific_gas_constant
1400    K = pipe.K(Re(fluid, m_dot_g, pipe.ID, pipe.area))
1401    A = pipe.area
1402    m_dot = A * ((P1**2-P2**2)/(R*T*(2*log(P1/P2)+K)))**0.5
1403    if abs(m_dot-m_dot_g)/m_dot > tol:
1404        m_dot = m_dot_isot(fluid, pipe, P_out, m_dot, tol)
1405    return m_dot.to(ureg.g/ureg.s)
1406
1407
1408def dP_isot(m_dot, fluid, pipe, tol=1e-6):
1409    """Calculate pressure drop through piping for isothermal compressible
1410    flow.
1411
1412    See 4.4 of "Pipe flow, A Practical and Comprehensive Guide", Rennels,
1413    Hobart, Hudson, 2012.
1414
1415    Parameters
1416    ----------
1417    m_dot : Quantity {mass: 1, time: -1}
1418        mass flow rate
1419    fluid : ThermState
1420        Inlet fluid conditions
1421    pipe : Pipe
1422    tol : float
1423        Accuracy of the calculation.
1424
1425    Returns
1426    -------
1427    Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -2}
1428        Pressure drop
1429    """
1430    R = fluid.specific_gas_constant
1431    T = fluid.T
1432    P1 = fluid.P
1433    A = pipe.area
1434    K = pipe.K(Re(fluid, m_dot, pipe.ID, pipe.area))
1435    P2 = P1
1436    converged = False
1437    while not converged:
1438        sq_diff = m_dot**2*R*T/A**2 * (2*log(P1/P2)+K)
1439        P2_new = (P1**2 - sq_diff)**0.5
1440        converged = abs(P2_new-P2)/P2_new
1441        P2 = P2_new
1442        v = m_dot / (fluid.Dmass*A)
1443        if Mach(fluid, v) > 1/(fluid.gamma):
1444            raise ChokedFlow('K needs to be reduced to reach P2={P2:.3g~}')
1445    return P1 - P2
1446
1447
1448def Mach(fluid, v):
1449    """Calculate Mach number for given static conditions of the fluid.
1450
1451
1452    Parameters:
1453    -----------
1454    fluid : ThermState
1455        Fluid state at static temperature and pressure
1456    v : Quantity, {length: 1, time: -1}
1457    """
1458    M = v / fluid.speed_sound
1459    return float(M)
1460
1461
1462def Mach_total(fluid, m_dot, area):
1463    """Calculate Mach number for total temperature and pressure.
1464
1465    Parameters:
1466    -----------
1467    fluid : ThermState
1468        Fluid state at total temperature and pressure
1469    """
1470    k = float(fluid.gamma)
1471    v = velocity(fluid, m_dot, area)
1472    T = fluid.T
1473    P = fluid.P
1474    Z = fluid.Z
1475    R = ureg.molar_gas_constant / fluid.molar_mass
1476    B = m_dot / area * (Z*R/k)**0.5
1477    M_core = float(B * T**0.5 / P)
1478
1479    def to_solve(Msq):
1480        try:
1481            res = M_core**2 * (1+Msq*(k-1)/2)**((k+1)/(k-1)) - Msq
1482        except RuntimeWarning:
1483            res = float('nan')
1484        return res
1485    bracket = [0, 1]
1486    solution = root_scalar(to_solve, bracket=bracket)
1487    M_root = solution.root**0.5
1488    # Not sure if this is needed anymore
1489    T = fluid.T - v**2 / fluid.Cpmass
1490    if T < 0*ureg.K:
1491        raise HydraulicError(f'Negative static temperature: {T:.3g~}. Required '
1492                             f'speed {v.to(ureg.m/ureg.s):.3g~} cannot be achieved.')
1493    return M_root
1494
1495
1496def K_lim(M, k):
1497    """Calculate max resistance coefficient of a pipe.
1498    """
1499    if M == 0:
1500        raise ValueError('K_lim is undefined for Ma=0.')
1501    A = (1-M**2) / (k*M**2)
1502    B = (k+1)/(2*k)
1503    C = (k+1) * M**2
1504    D = 2 + (k-1) * M**2
1505    K = A + B * log(C/D)
1506    return K
1507
1508
1509def M_Klim(K, k):
1510    if K < 0:
1511        raise HydraulicError(f"Resistance coefficient value can't be less \
1512        than 0: {K}")
1513    K = float(K)
1514
1515    def to_solve(M):
1516        if M == 0:
1517            return float('-inf')
1518        return K - K_lim(M, k)
1519    bracket = [0, 1]
1520    solution = root_scalar(to_solve, bracket=bracket)
1521    M = solution.root
1522    return M
1523
1524
1525def M_complex(M, k):
1526    return 1 + M**2 * (k-1) / 2
1527
1528
1529def P_from_M(P1, M1, M2, k):
1530    """Calculate static pressure from inlet static pressure and Mach numbers."""
1531    PM1 = P1 * M1 * M_complex(M1, k)**0.5
1532    P2 = PM1 / (M2*M_complex(M2, k)**0.5)
1533    return P2
1534
1535
1536def P_total(P, M, k):
1537    """Calculate total pressure from static pressure."""
1538    return P * M_complex(M, k)**(k/(k-1))
1539
1540
1541def P_crit(P, M, k):
1542    """Calculate critical(sonic) pressure for the given static pressure and Ma."""
1543    M_crit_comp = (k+1) / (2+(k-1)*M**2)
1544    P_c = P * M / M_crit_comp**0.5
1545    return P_c
1546
1547
1548def dP_adiab(m_dot, fluid, pipe, state='total'):
1549    """Calculate pressure drop for isentropic flow given total inlet conditions.
1550
1551    """
1552    if state == 'total':
1553        M = Mach_total(fluid, m_dot, pipe.area)
1554    elif state == 'static':
1555        v = velocity(fluid, m_dot, pipe.area)
1556        M = Mach(fluid, v)
1557    K_limit = K_lim(M, fluid.gamma)
1558    Re_ = Re(fluid, m_dot, pipe.ID, pipe.area)
1559    K_pipe = pipe.K(Re_)
1560    K_left = K_limit - K_pipe
1561    if K_left < 0:
1562        raise ChokedFlow(f'Flow is choked at K={float(K_limit):.3g} with given '
1563                         f'K={float(K_pipe):.3g}. Reduce hydraulic resistance or'
1564                         ' mass flow.')
1565    M_end = M_Klim(K_left, fluid.gamma)
1566    # TODO This assumes isentropic flow, i.e., no friction. For adiabatic flow only Ttotal will be constant.
1567    # See White 9.3 for details.
1568    P_static_end = P_from_M(fluid.P, M, M_end, fluid.gamma)
1569    return fluid.P - P_static_end
1570
1571
1572def m_dot_adiab(fluid, pipe, P_out=P_NTP, state='total'):
1573    """Calculate mass flow rate through piping for adiabatic compressible
1574    flow.
1575
1576    Parameters
1577    ----------
1578    fluid : ThermState
1579        Inlet fluid conditions
1580    pipe : Pipe
1581    P_out : Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -2}
1582        Outlet pressure
1583
1584    Returns
1585    -------
1586    Quantity {mass: 1, time: -1}
1587        mass flow rate
1588    """
1589    k = fluid.gamma
1590    P1 = fluid.P
1591    P2 = P_out
1592
1593    def to_solve(m_dot_):
1594        m_dot = m_dot_ * ureg.kg/ureg.s
1595        if state == 'total':
1596            try:
1597                M1 = Mach_total(fluid, m_dot, pipe.area)
1598            except HydraulicError:
1599                return -1
1600        elif state == 'static':
1601            v = velocity(fluid, m_dot, pipe.area)
1602            M1 = Mach(fluid, v)
1603        P_crit1_ = P_crit(P1, M1, k).m_as(ureg.Pa)
1604        K_lim1 = K_lim(M1, k)
1605        Re_ = Re(fluid, m_dot, pipe.ID, pipe.area)
1606        K_lim2 = K_lim1 - pipe.K(Re_)
1607        if K_lim2 < 0:
1608            return -1
1609        M2 = M_Klim(K_lim2, k)
1610        P_crit2_ = P_crit(P2, M2, k).m_as(ureg.Pa)
1611        # TODO Only true for isentropic flow, for adiabatic Tcrit should be used
1612        result = P_crit1_ - P_crit2_
1613        return result
1614    bracket = [1e-10, 1e10]  # Limits search range
1615    solution = root_scalar(to_solve, bracket=bracket)
1616    m_dot = solution.root * ureg.kg/ureg.s
1617    return m_dot

1620def K_to_Cv(K, ID):
1621    """
1622    Calculate flow coefficient Cv based on resistance coefficient value K.
1623    Based on definition:
1624    Cv = Q*sqrt(rho/(d_P*rho_w))
1625    where Q - volumetric flow, rho - flow density
1626    rho_w - water density at 60 F
1627    d_P - pressure drop through the valve.
1628    [Cv] = gal/(min*(psi)**0.5)
1629    """
1630    A = pi*ID**2/4
1631    rho_w = 999*ureg('kg/m**3')  # Water density at 60 F
1632    # TODO move density to global const (or use ThermState)
1633    # Based on Crane TP-410 p. 2-10 and Darcy equation:
1634    Cv = A*(2/(K*rho_w))**0.5
1635    Cv.ito(ureg('gal/(min*(psi)**0.5)'))  # Convention accepted in the US
1636    return Cv
1637
1638
1639def Cv_to_K(Cv, ID):
1640    """
1641    Calculate resistance coefficient K based on flow coefficient value Cv.
1642    Based on definition:
1643    Cv = Q*sqrt(rho/(d_P*rho_w))
1644    where Q - volumetric flow, rho - flow density
1645    rho_w - water density at 60 F
1646    d_P - pressure drop through the valve.
1647    [Cv] = gal/(min*(psi)**0.5)
1648    """
1649    if isinstance(Cv, (int, float)):  # Check if dimensionless input
1650        Cv = Cv*ureg('gal/(min*(psi)**0.5)')  # Convention accepted in the US
1651    A = pi*ID**2/4
1652    rho_w = 999*ureg('kg/m**3')  # Water density at 60 F
1653    # Based on Crane TP-410 p. 2-10 and Darcy equation:
1654    K = 2*A**2/(Cv**2*rho_w)
1655    return K.to(ureg.dimensionless)
1656
1657
1658def beta(d1, d2):
1659    """
1660    Calculate beta = d/D for contraction or enlargement.
1661    """
1662    beta_ = min(d1, d2)/max(d1, d2)
1663    return float(beta_)

1666def equivalent_orifice(m_dot, dP, fluid=AIR):
1667    """
1668    Calculate ID for the equivalent square edge orifice (Cd = 0.61) for given
1669    flow and pressure drop.
1670    """
1671    Cd = 0.61
1672    rho = fluid.Dmass
1673    ID = 2 * (m_dot/(pi*Cd*(2*dP*rho)**0.5))**0.5
1674    return ID.to(ureg.inch)

1677def velocity(fluid, m_dot, area):
1678    """Calculate velocity of fluid with given local parameters."""
1679
1680    return m_dot/(area*fluid.Dmass)

1683def piping_stress(tube, P_diff, *, E, W, Y):
1684    """Calculate piping stress for given pressure and pipe material.
1685
1686    Based on B31.3 304.1.
1687
1688    Parameters
1689    ----------
1690    P_diff : ureg.Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -2}
1691        Differential internal pressure, absolute
1692
1693    Returns
1694    -------
1695    ureg.Quantity {mass: 1, length: -1, time: -2}
1696        Piping stress
1697    """
1698    logger.warning('Deprecated.')
1699    P = P_diff
1700    D = tube.OD
1701    t = tube.wall - tube.c
1702    S = P / (E*W) * (D/(2*t) - Y)
1703    return S.to(ureg.psi)

1711def pressure_req_thick(tube, P_diff, I=1, *, S, E, W, Y):
1712    """
1713    Calculate minimum required thickness for given pressure and tube and material
1714    based on B31.3 304.1.
1715
1716    Parameters
1717    ----------
1718    tube : Tube
1719    P_diff : ureg.Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -2}
1720        Differential internal pressure.
1721    I : float, optional
1722       Pipe bend coefficient per 304.2.1; for a straight pipe equals 1.
1723    S : ureg.Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -2}
1724        Stress value for material from Table A-1A/A-1B.
1725    E : float
1726        Quality factor from Table A-1A/A-1B.
1727    W : float
1728        Weld joint strength reduction factor in accordance with 302.3.5(e).
1729    Y : float
1730        Coefficient from Table 304.1.1.
1731
1732    Returns
1733    -------
1734    ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
1735        Minimum required wall thickness.
1736
1737    Notes
1738    -----
1739    The formula for calculating the required thickness is:
1740
1741    .. math:: t_m = \\frac{P D}{2 (S E W/I + P Y)} + c
1742
1743    where:
1744      - \( t \) is the minimum required wall thickness,
1745      - \( P \) is the differential internal pressure,
1746      - \( D \) is the outside diameter of the tube,
1747      - \( S \) is the allowable stress of the material,
1748      - \( E \) is the quality factor,
1749      - \( W \) is the weld joint strength reduction factor,
1750      - \( I \) is the pipe bend coefficient.
1751      - \( Y \) is the coefficient from Table 304.1.1.
1752
1753    If the calculated thickness \( t \) is greater than or equal to \( D/6 \) or if \( P/(S E) \) is greater than 0.385, the design thickness must be calculated in accordance with B31.3 304.1.2 (b).
1754
1755    Examples
1756    --------
1757    >>> import CryoToolBox as ctb
1758    >>> u = ctb.ureg
1759    >>> tube = ctb.piping.Tube(4*u.inch, wall=0.065*u.inch, c=0.125*u.inch)
1760    >>> P_diff = 200 * u.psi
1761    >>> S = 20000 * u.psi
1762    >>> E = 0.85
1763    >>> W = 1.0
1764    >>> Y = 0.4
1765    >>> pressure_req_thick(tube, P_diff, 1, S=S, E=E, W=W, Y=Y)
1766    <Quantity(0.148419204, 'inch')>
1767    """
1768    D = tube.OD
1769    P = P_diff.to_base_units()
1770    t = P * D / (2*(S*E*W/I + P*Y))
1771    if (t >= D/6) or (P/(S*E)) > 0.385:
1772        logger.error('Calculate design thickness in accordance \
1773        with B31.3 304.1.2 (b)')
1774        return None
1775    tm = t + tube.c
1776    return tm.to(ureg.inch)
1777
1778
1779def I_intrados(R1, D):
1780    """Calculate coefficient I at the intrados of a bend per B31.3 304.2.1 (3d).
1781
1782    Parameters
1783    ----------
1784    R1 : float
1785        bend radius of a pipe bend
1786    D : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
1787        Outside diameter of a pipe
1788
1789    Returns
1790    -------
1791    float
1792    """
1793
1794    I = (4*(R1/D)-1) / (4*(R1/D)-2)
1795    return I
1796

1798def I_extrados(R1, D):
1799    """Calculate coefficient I at the extrados of a bend per B31.3 304.2.1 (3e).
1800
1801    Parameters
1802    ----------
1803    R1 : float
1804        bend radius of a pipe bend
1805    D : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
1806        Outside diameter of a pipe
1807
1808    Returns
1809    -------
1810    float
1811    """
1812
1813    I = (4*(R1/D)+1) / (4*(R1/D)+2)
1814    return I

1817def pressure_rating(tube, *, S, E, W, Y):
1818    """Calculate internal pressure rating.
1819
1820    Based on B31.3 304.1.
1821
1822    Returns
1823    -------
1824    ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
1825        Minimum required wall thickness.
1826    """
1827    D = tube.OD
1828    t = tube.T - tube.c
1829    P = 2 * t * S * E * W / (D-2*Y*t)
1830    return P.to(ureg.psi)

1833def calculate_branch_reinforcement(header, branch, P_diff, beta=Q_('90 deg'),
1834                                   Tr=Q_('0 in'), Lr=Q_('0 in'), d1=None,
1835                                   *, S, E, W, Y):
1836    """Calculate reinforcement and available area for given branch pipe and
1837    reinforcing ring thickness, Tr.
1838
1839    Parameters
1840    ----------
1841    header : Pipe
1842        Header pipe/tube
1843    branch : Pipe
1844        Branch pipe/tube
1845    P_diff : ureg.Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -2}
1846        Differential internal pressure in pipe and branch
1847    beta : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}
1848        Smaller angle between axes of branch and run
1849    d1 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
1850        Effective length removed from pipe at branch (opening for branch)
1851    Tr : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
1852        Minimum thickness of reinforcing ring
1853    Lr : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
1854        Length of reinforcing ring along the run pipe.
1855
1856    Returns
1857    -------
1858    None
1859
1860    """
1861    # B31.3 has no specification which allowance to use
1862    # Using header allowance for header
1863    # and branch allowance for branch
1864    Dh = header.OD
1865    Th = header.T
1866    tmh = pressure_req_thick(header, P_diff, S=S, E=E, W=W, Y=Y)
1867    c = header.c
1868    th = tmh - c
1869    result = _reinforcement_area(P_diff, Dh, Th, th, c, branch, beta, Tr, Lr, d1,
1870                                 S, E, W, Y)
1871    return result
1872
1873def _reinforcement_area(P_diff, Dh, Th, th, c, branch, beta, Tr, Lr, d1, S, E,
1874                        W, Y):
1875    Db = branch.OD
1876    Tb = branch.T
1877    tmb = pressure_req_thick(branch, P_diff, S=S, E=E, W=W, Y=Y)
1878    C = branch.c
1879    tb = tmb - C
1880    if d1 is None:
1881        d1 = (Db - 2*(Tb-C)) / sin(beta)
1882    d2 = _half_width(d1, Th, c, Tb, C, Dh)
1883    A1 = th * d1 * (2-sin(beta))
1884    A2 = (2*d2-d1) * (Th - th - c)
1885    L4 = min(2.5*(Th-c), 2.5*(Tb-C)+Tr)
1886    A3 = 2 * L4 * (Tb-tb-C)/sin(beta)
1887    # TODO Add handling of different allowable stresses for header and branch
1888    # A_3 = 2 * L_4 * (T_b-t_b-c)/sin(beta) * branch.S / header.S
1889    # TODO Add reinforcement area due to welds
1890    A4 = Tr * (Lr-Db/sin(beta))
1891    return ReinforcementAreaResult(A1, A2, A3, A4, d2, A2+A3+A4>A1)
1892
1893def _half_width(d1, Th, c, Tb, C, Dh):
1894    """
1895    Calculate 'half width' of reinforcement zone per B31.3 304.3.3.
1896    """
1897    d2_a = (Tb-C) + (Th-c) + d1/2
1898    return min(max(d1, d2_a), Dh)
1899

1901def calculate_closure_reinforcement(Tp, tp, c, branch, P_diff, beta=Q_('90 deg'),
1902                                 Tr=Q_('0 in'), Lr=Q_('0 in'), d1=None,
1903                                    *, S, E, W, Y):
1904    """
1905
1906    Tp : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
1907        Plate thickness measured or minimum in accordance with purchase specification.
1908    tp : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
1909        Pressure design thickness of the plate.
1910    """
1911    result = _reinforcement_area(P_diff, float('inf')*ureg.m, Tp, tp, c, branch,
1912                                 beta, Tr, Lr, d1, S, E, W, Y)
1913    return result

1916def G_nozzle(fluid, P_out=P_NTP, n_steps=20):
1917    """Calculate mass flux through a converging nozzle using direct integration
1918    method.
1919
1920    This method is recommended for relief valve sizing.
1921
1922    Parameters
1923    ----------
1924
1925    Returns
1926    -------
1927
1928    """
1929    fluid_temp = fluid.copy()
1930    P1_ = fluid.P.m_as(ureg.Pa)
1931    P2_ = P_out.m_as(ureg.Pa)
1932    S = fluid.Smass
1933
1934    def v(P_):
1935        P = P_ * ureg.Pa
1936        fluid_temp.update_kw(P=P, Smass=S)
1937        rho = fluid_temp.Dmass.m_as(ureg.kg/ureg.m**3)
1938        return 1/rho
1939
1940    dP = (P1_-P2_) / n_steps
1941    P_ = P1_
1942    # temp = []
1943    G_max = 0
1944    while P_ > P2_:
1945        G = 1/v(P_) * (-2*quad(v, P1_, P_)[0])**0.5
1946        # temp.append((G, (P_*ureg.Pa).m_as(ureg.psi)))
1947        if G >= G_max:
1948            G_max = G
1949        else:
1950            break
1951        P_ -= dP
1952    G_max *= ureg.kg/(ureg.s*ureg.m**2)
1953    return G_max

1956def volume(piping):
1957    """Calculate volume inside piping."""
1958    result = []
1959    pipe_type = (Pipe, VJPipe, CorrugatedPipe, Tube, Annulus, Elbow)
1960    # TODO remove elbows and tees after merge
1961    for pipe in piping:
1962        if isinstance(pipe, pipe_type):
1963            result.append((str(pipe),
1964                            f'{pipe.L.to(ureg.ft).magnitude:.3g}',
1965                            f'{pipe.volume.to(ureg.ft**3).magnitude:.3g}'))
1966    return result

1969def piping_stored_energy(fluid, piping):
1970    """Calculate stored energy of the piping.
1971
1972    Uses 8 diameters rule as per ASME PCC-2 2018 501-IV-3 (a)."""
1973    volume = 0 * ureg.m**3
1974    for tube in piping:
1975        # Smaller of 8*ID and actual length
1976        length = min(tube.L, 8*tube.ID)
1977        area = circle_area(tube.ID)
1978        volume = max(volume, area*length)
1979    return stored_energy(fluid, volume)

1982def Cv_to_Kv(Cv):
1983    """
1984    Convert Cv (flow coefficient in US units) to Kv (flow coefficient in metric units).
1985
1986    Parameters
1987    ----------
1988    Cv : float
1989        Flow coefficient expressed in US units gal/(min*psi**0.5).
1990
1991    Returns
1992    -------
1993    float
1994        Flow coefficient expressed in metric units (m³/(h*bar**0.5)).
1995    """
1996    Cv *= ureg.gal / (ureg.min * ureg.psi**0.5)
1997    return Cv.m_as(ureg.m**3 / (ureg.h * ureg.bar**0.5))

 81        """Generate tube object.
 82
 83        Parameters

488class Elbow(Tube):
489    """
490    NPS elbow fitting.
491    MRO makes method K from PipeElbow class to override method from Pipe class.
492    """
493    def __init__(self, OD, wall=0*ureg.inch, c=0*ureg.inch, R_D=1.5, N=1,
494                 angle=90*ureg.deg):
495        """Generate a tube elbow object.
496
497        Parameters
498        ----------
499        OD : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
500            Outer diameter of the tube.
501        wall : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
502            Wall thickness of the tube.
503        R_D : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
504            Elbow radius/diameter ratio
505        N : int
506            Number of elbows in the pipeline
507        angle : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}
508            Number of elbows in the pipeline
509        """
510        self.R_D = R_D
511        self.N = N
512        self.angle = angle
513        super().__init__(OD, wall, L=0*ureg.m, c=c)
514        self.L = R_D*self.ID*angle
515        self.type = 'Tube elbow'
516
517    def K(self, Re_):
518        """
519        Pressure drop in an elbow fitting.
520        Based on Handbook of Hydraulic Resistance by I.E. Idelchik.
521        """
522        if self.angle <= 70*ureg.deg:
523            A1 = 0.9*sin(self.angle)
524        elif self.angle == 90*ureg.deg:
525            A1 = 1
526        elif self.angle >= 100*ureg.deg:
527            A1 = 0.7+0.35*self.angle/(90*ureg.deg)
528        else:
529            logger.error('''Improper bend angle for elbow.
530            90 degrees used instead: {}'''.format(self.angle))
531            A1 = 1
532
533        if self.R_D < 1:
534            B1 = 0.21*(self.R_D)**(-0.25)
535        else:
536            B1 = 0.21*(self.R_D)**(-0.5)
537
538        C1 = 1  # use different value for non-axis symmetric
539        # Friction losses in the elbow
540        K_frict = super().K(Re_)
541        return (A1*B1*C1+K_frict)*self.N
542
543    def __str__(self):
544        return f'{self.N}x {self.type}, {self.OD}"x{self.wall}", ' + \
545            f'{self.angle.to(ureg.deg)}, R_D = {self.R_D}'

class PipingTransition(PipingElement): 
698class PipingTransition(PipingElement):
699    """
700    Base class for pipe diameter transitions (contractions and enlargements).
701    """
702
703    def _init_transition(self, ID1, ID2, theta, transition_type):
704        """
705        Common initialization for diameter transitions.
706
707        Parameters
708        ----------
709        ID1 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
710            Upstream pipe inside diameter.
711        ID2 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
712            Downstream pipe inside diameter.
713        theta : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}
714            Transition angle.
715        transition_type : str
716            Type of transition ('Contraction' or 'Enlargement').
717        """
718        # Validate angle (common to both)
719        if theta <= 0*ureg.deg or theta > 180*ureg.deg:
720            raise ValueError(f"Transition angle must be in range (0°, 180°], "
721                           f"got {theta}")
722
723        self.ID1 = ID1
724        self.ID2 = ID2
725        self.theta = theta
726        self.beta = beta(ID1, ID2)
727        self.type = transition_type
728        self.OD = None
729
730        # Use smaller diameter for area reference
731        self.ID = min(ID1, ID2)
732        self._area = circle_area(self.ID)
733
734        # Calculate axial length
735        self.L = abs(ID1 - ID2) / (2 * tan(theta/2))
736
737        # Calculate internal volume (truncated cone)
738        r1 = ID1 / 2
739        r2 = ID2 / 2
740        self.volume = pi * self.L / 3 * (r1**2 + r1*r2 + r2**2)
741
742    def __str__(self):
743        """
744        String representation of the piping transition.
745
746        Returns
747        -------
748        str
749            Human-readable description of the contraction.
750        """
751        return (f'{self.type}, {self.theta.to(ureg.deg)} from '
752                f'{self.ID1.to(ureg.inch):.3f} to {self.ID2.to(ureg.inch):.3f}')
753
754    def __repr__(self):
755        """
756        Detailed string representation for debugging.
757
758        Returns
759        -------
760        str
761            Detailed representation showing all key parameters.
762        """
763        return (f"Contraction(ID1={self.ID1}, ID2={self.ID2}, "
764                f"theta={self.theta})")

767class Contraction(PipingTransition):
768    """
769    Sudden and gradual pipe contraction fitting based on Crane TP-410.
770
771    This class represents pipe contractions that reduce flow area from a larger
772    upstream pipe to a smaller downstream pipe. The pressure loss coefficient
773    is calculated based on the contraction angle and diameter ratio according
774    to Crane TP-410 standards.
775
776    Parameters
777    ----------
778    ID1 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
779        Inside diameter of upstream (larger) pipe.
780    ID2 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
781        Inside diameter of downstream (smaller) pipe.
782    theta : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}, optional
783        Total contraction angle (included angle), by default 180°.
784        Valid range is 0° < theta ≤ 180°.
785
786    Attributes
787    ----------
788    beta : float
789        Diameter ratio (ID2/ID1), dimensionless.
790    theta : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}
791        Contraction angle.
792    type : str
793        Element type identifier.
794    ID1 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
795        Upstream pipe inside diameter.
796    ID2 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
797        Downstream pipe inside diameter.
798    ID : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
799        Minimum (downstream) inside diameter.
800    L : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
801        Axial length of contraction.
802    volume : ureg.Quantity {length: 3}
803        Internal volume of the contraction.
804
805    Notes
806    -----
807    The pressure loss coefficient K is calculated using different formulas
808    depending on the contraction angle:
809
810    For θ ≤ 45°:
811    .. math:: K = 0.8 \\sin(\\theta/2) (1 - \\beta^2)
812
813    For 45° < θ ≤ 180°:
814    .. math:: K = 0.5 (1 - \\beta^2) \\sqrt{\\sin(\\theta/2)}
815
816    Where β = ID2/ID1 is the diameter ratio.
817
818    The axial length is calculated as:
819    .. math:: L = \\frac{|ID_1 - ID_2|}{2 \\tan(\\theta/2)}
820
821    References
822    ----------
823    Crane Technical Paper No. 410 (TP-410), Flow of Fluids Through Valves,
824    Fittings, and Pipe, Section A-26.
825
826    Examples
827    --------
828    >>> import CryoToolBox as ctb
829    >>> u = ctb.ureg
830    >>> # Sudden contraction from 4" to 2" pipe
831    >>> contraction = ctb.piping.Contraction(4*u.inch, 2*u.inch)
832    >>> contraction.beta
833    0.5
834    >>> contraction.K()
835    0.375
836
837    >>> # Gradual 30° contraction
838    >>> gradual = ctb.piping.Contraction(4*u.inch, 2*u.inch, 30*u.deg)
839    >>> gradual.K()
840    0.1552...
841    """
842
843    def __init__(self, ID1, ID2, theta=ureg('180 deg')):
844        """
845        Initialize contraction fitting.
846
847        Parameters
848        ----------
849        ID1 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
850            Inside diameter of upstream pipe.
851        ID2 : ureg.Quantity {length: 1}
852            Inside diameter of downstream pipe.
853        theta : ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}, optional
854            Contraction angle, by default 180°.
855
856        Raises
857        ------
858        ValueError
859            If ID1 <= ID2 (not a contraction).
860            If theta is outside valid range (0°, 180°].
861        """
862        # Input validation
863        if ID1 <= ID2:
864            raise ValueError(f"ID1 ({ID1}) must be greater than ID2 ({ID2}) "
865                           "for a contraction")
866
867        if theta <= 0*ureg.deg or theta > 180*ureg.deg:
868            raise ValueError(f"Contraction angle must be in range (0°, 180°], "
869                           f"got {theta}")
870
871        self._init_transition(ID1, ID2, theta, 'Contraction')
872
873    @property
874    def area(self):
875        """
876        Cross-sectional area of the downstream (smaller) pipe.
877
878        Returns
879        -------
880        ureg.Quantity {length: 2}
881            Flow area based on downstream diameter.
882        """
883        return self._area
884
885    def K(self, Re=None):
886        """
887        Calculate pressure loss coefficient for the contraction.
888
889        Parameters
890        ----------
891        Re : float, optional
892            Reynolds number. Currently not implemented but reserved
893            for future Reynolds number corrections.
894
895        Returns
896        -------
897        float
898            Dimensionless pressure loss coefficient based on downstream
899            velocity head.
900
901        Notes
902        -----
903        The loss coefficient is calculated using Crane TP-410 formulas:
904
905        - For θ ≤ 45°: K = 0.8 sin(θ/2) (1 - β²)
906        - For θ > 45°: K = 0.5 (1 - β²) √sin(θ/2)
907
908        Where β = ID2/ID1 is the diameter ratio.
909
910        Raises
911        ------
912        ValueError
913            If theta > 180° (invalid contraction angle).
914
915        Examples
916        --------
917        >>> import CryoToolBox as ctb
918        >>> u = ctb.ureg
919        >>> contraction = Contraction(4*u.inch, 2*u.inch, 90*u.deg)
920        >>> contraction.K()
921        0.3153...
922        """
923        # TODO: Add Re handling for Reynolds number corrections
924        if Re is not None:
925            logger.warning("Reynolds number correction not yet implemented")
926
927        if self.theta <= 45*ureg.deg:
928            # Crane TP-410 A-26, Formula 1 for gradual contractions
929            K_ = 0.8 * sin(self.theta/2) * (1 - self.beta**2)
930        elif self.theta <= 180*ureg.deg:
931            # Crane TP-410 A-26, Formula 2 for sudden contractions
932            K_ = 0.5 * (1 - self.beta**2) * sqrt(sin(self.theta/2))
933        else:
934            raise ValueError(f'Contraction angle cannot exceed 180°, '
935                           f'got {self.theta.to(ureg.deg)}')
936
937        return float(K_)

Sudden and gradual pipe contraction fitting based on Crane TP-410.

This class represents pipe contractions that reduce flow area from a larger upstream pipe to a smaller downstream pipe. The pressure loss coefficient is calculated based on the contraction angle and diameter ratio according to Crane TP-410 standards.

Parameters
  • ID1 : ureg.Quantity {length (1}): Inside diameter of upstream (larger) pipe.
  • ID2 : ureg.Quantity {length (1}): Inside diameter of downstream (smaller) pipe.
  • theta (ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}, optional): Total contraction angle (included angle), by default 180°. Valid range is 0° < theta ≤ 180°.
Attributes
  • beta (float): Diameter ratio (ID2/ID1), dimensionless.
  • theta (ureg.Quantity {dimensionless}): Contraction angle.
  • type (str): Element type identifier.
  • ID1 : ureg.Quantity {length (1}): Upstream pipe inside diameter.
  • ID2 : ureg.Quantity {length (1}): Downstream pipe inside diameter.
  • ID : ureg.Quantity {length (1}): Minimum (downstream) inside diameter.
  • L : ureg.Quantity {length (1}): Axial length of contraction.
  • volume : ureg.Quantity {length (3}): Internal volume of the contraction.
Notes

The pressure loss coefficient K is calculated using different formulas depending on the contraction angle:

For θ ≤ 45°: $$K = 0.8 \sin(\theta/2) (1 - \beta^2)$$

For 45° < θ ≤ 180°: $$K = 0.5 (1 - \beta^2) \sqrt{\sin(\theta/2)}$$

Where β = ID2/ID1 is the diameter ratio.

The axial length is calculated as: $$L = \frac{|ID_1 - ID_2|}{2 \tan(\theta/2)}$$

References

Crane Technical Paper No. 410 (TP-410), Flow of Fluids Through Valves, Fittings, and Pipe, Section A-26.

Examples
>>> import CryoToolBox as ctb
>>> u = ctb.ureg
>>> # Sudden contraction from 4" to 2" pipe
>>> contraction = ctb.piping.Contraction(4*u.inch, 2*u.inch)
>>> contraction.beta
0.5
>>> contraction.K()
0.375

>>> # Gradual 30° contraction
>>> gradual = ctb.piping.Contraction(4*u.inch, 2*u.inch, 30*u.deg)
>>> gradual.K()
0.1552...

1090    def __init__(self, Springs, Plate, Supply_pipe):
1091        """
1092        Initiate Parallel Plate instance.
1093        Parallel Plate relief valve designed by Fermilab
1094
1095        Springs: dictionary containing 'N' - number of springs, 'k' - spring rate, and 'dx_precomp' - pre-compression length
1096        Plate: dictionary containing 'OD_plate' - OD of the plate, 'OD_O_ring' - OD of the O-Ring installed, and 'W_plate' - plate weight
1097        Supply_pipe: Pipe/Tube object of upstream pipe
1098        """
1099        self.Springs = Springs
1100        self.Plate = Plate
1101        self.Supply_pipe = Supply_pipe
1102
1103    def P_set(self):
1104        """"
1105        Calculate set (lift) pressure of the Parallel Plate relief
1106        """
1107        # Before lifting pressure affects area within O-Ring OD
1108        A_lift = pi * self.Plate['OD_O_ring']**2 / 4
1109        F_precomp = self.Springs['N'] * self.Springs['k'] *\
1110            self.Springs['dx_precomp']
1111        # Force required to lift the plate
1112        F_lift = F_precomp + self.Plate['W_plate']
1113        self.F_lift = F_lift
1114        P_set = F_lift / A_lift
1115        return P_set.to(ureg.psi)
1116
1117    def P_open(self):
1118        """
1119        Calculate pressure required to fully open Parallel Plate relief
1120        """
1121        # compression required to provide vent area equal to supply pipe area
1122        dx_open = self.Supply_pipe.area / (pi*self.Plate['OD_plate'])
1123        # Force at fully open
1124        F_open = self.F_lift = self.Springs['N'] * self.Springs['k'] * dx_open
1125        # At fully open pressure is distributed as:
1126        # Full pressure for up to supply pipe diameter
1127        # Linear fall off up to plate OD
1128        A_open = self.Supply_pipe.area + pi/8*(self.Plate['OD_plate']**2 -
1129                                               self.Supply_pipe.ID**2)
1130        P_open = F_open / A_open
1131        return P_open.to(ureg.psi)

def churchill(Re_, eps_r): 
1163def churchill(Re_, eps_r):
1164    """Calculate Darcy friction factor using modified Churchill formula.
1165    See 8.5.2 of "Pipe flow, A Practical and Comprehensive Guide", Rennels,
1166    Hobart, Hudson, 2012.
1167
1168    Parameters
1169    ----------
1170    Re_ : float or Quantity {dimensionless}
1171        Reynolds number
1172    eps_r : float or Quantity {dimensionless}
1173        Relative roughness of the pipe
1174
1175    Returns
1176    -------
1177    float
1178        Darcy friction coefficient
1179    """
1180    A1 = 0.883 * log(Re_)**1.282 / Re_**1.007
1181    A2 = 0.27 * eps_r
1182    A3 = - 110 * eps_r / Re_
1183    A = (0.8687 * log(A1+A2+A3))**16
1184    B = (13269 / Re_)**16
1185    f = ((64/Re_)**12 + 1/(A+B)**(3/2))**(1/12)
1186    return f

def serghide(Re_, eps_r): 
1189def serghide(Re_, eps_r):
1190    """Calculate Darcy friction factor using Serghide solution to
1191    Colebrook equation.
1192
1193    See Crane TP-410 2013, equation 6-6.
1194
1195    Parameters
1196    ----------
1197    Re_ : float or Quantity {dimensionless}
1198        Reynolds number
1199    eps_r : float or Quantity {dimensionless}
1200        Relative roughness of the pipe
1201
1202    Returns
1203    -------
1204    float
1205        Darcy friction coefficient
1206    """
1207    A = -2 * log10(eps_r/3.7+12/Re_)
1208    B = -2 * log10(eps_r/3.7+2.51*A/Re_)
1209    C = -2 * log10(eps_r/3.7+2.51*B/Re_)
1210    f = (A - (B-A)**2/(C-2*B+A))**(-2)
1211    return f

Calculate pressure drop using the Darcy-Weisbach equation.

This function calculates the pressure drop across a pipe fitting or section using the standard form of the Darcy-Weisbach equation with a resistance coefficient K.

Parameters
  • K (float): Dimensionless resistance coefficient (loss coefficient). Typical values:

    • 90° elbow: K ≈ 0.9

  • Steady-state conditions
  • K value appropriate for the flow conditions (Reynolds number)

The pressure drop represents the mechanical energy loss due to friction, turbulence, and flow separation.

1340def m_dot_incomp(fluid, piping, P_out=P_NTP, guess=1*ureg.g/ureg.s):
1341    '''Calculate mass flow through the piping using initial conditions
1342    at the beginning of piping.
1343
1344    Calculation is based on Crane TP-410, p. 1.9.
1345    Net expansion factor Y is conservatively assumed as 1.
1346    Mass flow is calculated using Darcy equation.
1347
1348    Parameters
1349    ----------
1350    P_out : ureg.Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -1}
1351        Exit pressure of the piping.
1352    guess : ureg.Quantity {mass: 1, time: -1}
1353        guess value for the mass flow rate
1354
1355    Returns
1356    -------
1357    ureg.Quantity : {mass: 1, time: -1}
1358    '''
1359    P_0 = fluid.P
1360    if P_0 <= P_out:
1361        raise HydraulicError(f'Input pressure less or equal to output: \
1362        {P_0.to(ureg.Pa):.3g}, {P_out.to(ureg.Pa):.3g}')
1363    def to_solve(m_dot_gs, P_in_Pa, P_out_Pa):
1364        dP_calc = dP_incomp(m_dot_gs*ureg.g/ureg.s, fluid, piping)
1365        dP_given = P_in_Pa - P_out_Pa
1366        return dP_given - dP_calc.m_as(ureg.Pa)
1367    P_in_Pa = P_0.m_as(ureg.Pa)
1368    P_out_Pa = P_out.m_as(ureg.Pa)
1369    args = (P_in_Pa, P_out_Pa)  # arguments passed to to_solve
1370    x0 = guess.m_as(ureg.g/ureg.s)
1371    x1 = x0 * 2  # Usually doubling the flow is OK estimate
1372    solution = root_scalar(to_solve, args, x0=x0, x1=x1)
1373    m_dot_ = solution.root * ureg.g/ureg.s
1374    return m_dot_

1377def m_dot_isot(fluid, pipe, P_out=P_NTP, m_dot_g=1*ureg.g/ureg.s, tol=1e-6):
1378    """Calculate mass flow rate through piping for isothermal compressible
1379    flow.
1380
1381    See 4.4 of "Pipe flow, A Practical and Comprehensive Guide", Rennels,
1382    Hobart, Hudson, 2012.
1383
1384    Parameters
1385    ----------
1386    fluid : ThermState
1387        Inlet fluid conditions
1388    pipe : Pipe
1389    P_out : ureg.Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -1}
1390        Exit pressure of the piping.
1391
1392    Returns
1393    -------

1396    """

1398    P2 = P_out

1410    """Calculate pressure drop through piping for isothermal compressible
1411    flow.
1412
1413    See 4.4 of "Pipe flow, A Practical and Comprehensive Guide", Rennels,
1414    Hobart, Hudson, 2012.
1415
1416    Parameters
1417    ----------
1418    m_dot : Quantity {mass: 1, time: -1}
1419        mass flow rate
1420    fluid : ThermState
1421        Inlet fluid conditions
1422    pipe : Pipe
1423    tol : float
1424        Accuracy of the calculation.
1425
1426    Returns
1427    -------
1428    Quantity {length: -1, mass: 1, time: -2}
1429        Pressure drop
1430    """
1431    R = fluid.specific_gas_constant
1432    T = fluid.T
1433    P1 = fluid.P
1434    A = pipe.area
1435    K = pipe.K(Re(fluid, m_dot, pipe.ID, pipe.area))
1436    P2 = P1
1437    converged = False
1438    while not converged:
1439        sq_diff = m_dot**2*R*T/A**2 * (2*log(P1/P2)+K)

1444        if Mach(fluid, v) > 1/(fluid.gamma):

1446    return P1 - P2

def K_lim(M, k): 
1497def K_lim(M, k):
1498    """Calculate max resistance coefficient of a pipe.
1499    """
1500    if M == 0:
1501        raise ValueError('K_lim is undefined for Ma=0.')
1502    A = (1-M**2) / (k*M**2)
1503    B = (k+1)/(2*k)
1504    C = (k+1) * M**2
1505    D = 2 + (k-1) * M**2
1506    K = A + B * log(C/D)
1507    return K
